Why You Should Get Out of Your Business

Don’t spend all your time running your business.

*“Say what?”*

Here’s how it works: You can either be IN the system or working ON the system, but you can’t do both at the same time. You will never fix a system that you live in permanently.

If you spend all your time running your business, you’ll never be able to fix any problems in *how* you run your business. 

**You should regularly step ‘outside’ of your business and review specific systems.**

* Look at your system for finding prospects.  
- Are you bringing in new leads (aka, potential sales)? Or have you plateaued, with few new customers coming in?

* Look at your system for converting leads into sales.  
- Are you letting leads drop? If so, why? Are you too busy? Are you focused on other things which could be given lower priority?  
- Are you selling your product or service too short?  
- Is your demeanor or lack of professionalism turning people off?


* Look at your system for fulfilling these orders.  
- Are you keeping up with the books? Do you have an established system to process payments? If not, why? Do you need to hire a secretary?  
- Do you have a system for scheduling clientele appointments or phone-call reminders?  
- Do you have a system for scheduling employee work hours, off-days, and clocked-time?


* Look your system for getting feedback from customers.  
- Do you have anywhere for customers to submit feedback?  
- Are you sending follow-up emails or phone-calls?


* Look at your system for staying in touch with customers.  
- Do you have a mailing and/or emailing list?  
- Do you have a Facebook page where you regularly interact with your followers?

Asking these or similar questions will give you tremendous insight into where you can improve the efficiency and reliability of your systems. Furthermore, you will be able to catch small problems before they become big problems. Solving your problem with inbound sales can prevent a cash flow crises three months down the road.

If you’re serious about maintaining your business for the long haul, take the time to step outside of the business to refine your systems.
